        "title": "Peter at Joppa — Tabitha, arise",
        "range": "9:36-43",
        "excerpt": "But Peter sent them all out and knelt down and prayed, and turning to the body, he said, \"Tabitha, arise.\" And she opened her eyes, and when she saw Peter, she sat up.",
        "body": "Luke moves the camera 12 miles further to the coast — Joppa, the chief Mediterranean port of Judea (modern Jaffa, now absorbed into Tel Aviv). At Joppa lives *a disciple named Tabitha (which translated in Greek is called Dorcas)* — both names mean *gazelle* (Aramaic *Tabitha*, Greek *Dorkas*). Luke gives both names because his audience is bilingual, and the bilingual name itself signals a believer who lives at the Aramaic-Greek interface — exactly the cultural border Peter is being prepared to cross at Caesarea.\n\nTabitha is the only person in the New Testament called *mathetria* — the feminine form of *disciple*. Luke uses the feminine deliberately; she is not merely *a woman who was a disciple* but *a female disciple* in her own right. Her ministry is described in two summary phrases: *abounding with deeds of kindness* (*ergon agathon* — good works) *and charity* (*eleemosune* — almsgiving) *which she continually did*. The imperfect tense *epoiei* (continually did) makes it the pattern of her life, not a one-time effort. She is a working-class believer whose vocation was hand-sewn clothing for the poor of her city.\n\nShe falls sick and dies. Her body is washed (the ordinary preparation for Jewish burial) and laid in an upper room — a deliberate delay of burial. The community has already heard that Peter is in Lydda (less than a day's walk away) and sends two men to summon him with the request *me okneses dielthein* — *do not delay in coming to us*. The unstated expectation is unmistakable: they have heard about Aeneas; they hope for resurrection.\n\nPeter arrives and is brought to the upper room. *All the widows stood beside him, weeping and showing all the tunics and garments that Dorcas used to make while she was with them.* The detail is heartbreaking and theologically loaded. The widows in the early church were a vulnerable class (cf. Acts 6:1; 1 Timothy 5:3-16); Tabitha had clothed them. They are not merely grieving; they are displaying the testimony of her ministry. Her good works are present in the room as cloth — the physical manifestation of her *eleemosune*.\n\nPeter's response is methodically modeled on Jesus's raising of Jairus's daughter in Mark 5:35-43. *Peter sent them all out* — as Jesus *put them all out* (Mark 5:40). *Knelt down and prayed* — Peter does not assume the power is his; he asks. *And turning to the body, he said, \"Tabitha, arise.\"* The Greek is *Tabitha, anastethi*. In Aramaic that command would be *Tabitha, qumi* — phonetically nearly identical to Jesus's *Talitha koum* (*little girl, arise*) in Mark 5:41. The two-word resurrection command is unmistakable. Peter is doing exactly what he saw Jesus do, with one Aramaic syllable changed (*talitha* — little girl; *Tabitha* — the woman's name).\n\n*And she opened her eyes, and when she saw Peter, she sat up.* The progressive movement — eyes open, Peter recognized, sat up — is the deliberate detail of an eyewitness account. Peter gives her his hand and raises her up (*anistemi* once more — the chapter's third use of the resurrection verb as physical action); he calls the saints and widows (Luke pairs the two terms) and *presented her alive*. The verb *paristemi* (presented) is the same Paul will use of presenting believers mature in Christ (Colossians 1:28) and the resurrection body to God (Romans 12:1).\n\nThe effect: *It became known all over Joppa, and many believed in the Lord.* Resurrection produces faith. And then the chapter's quietly explosive final verse: *And Peter stayed many days in Joppa with a tanner named Simon.* A tanner's trade involved constant contact with the carcasses of dead animals; tanners were ritually unclean by Levitical standards (Leviticus 11:39-40) and socially marginal. Peter — apostle to the circumcision — staying as a guest in a tanner's house is itself a small, deliberate breach in the Jewish ceremonial barrier. The reader of Acts 9 cannot yet know that Cornelius's messengers are about to arrive at this very tanner's house (10:5-6). But Luke has placed Peter exactly where the next chapter needs him to be — and ceremonially loosened from the categories that the Cornelius episode will fully dismantle.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Mathetria* (female disciple, v. 36) — used only here in the New Testament; the feminine of *mathetes*. *Tabitha* (Aramaic) / *Dorkas* (Greek) — both mean *gazelle*; Luke gives both names for his bilingual audience. *Eleemosune* (charity, v. 36) — almsgiving, mercy in concrete form. *Anastethi* (arise, v. 40) — the imperative of *anistemi*, phonetically close to Jesus's Aramaic *Talitha koum* (Mark 5:41). *Burseus* (tanner, v. 43) — a ceremonially-suspect trade because of constant contact with dead animals (Leviticus 11:39-40). Peter's lodging there is the first quiet step toward Acts 10."
